# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sack-of-rome-410
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The **Adda** (Latin: *Abdua*, or *Addua*; Lombard: *Ada*, or *Adda*) is a river in North Italy, a tributary of the Po.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] It rises in the Alps near the border with Switzerland and flows through Lake Como.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The Adda joins the Po near Castelnuovo Bocca d'Adda, a few kilometers upstream of Cremona.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The river's length is 313 kilometres (194 mi).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The highest point of the drainage basin is the summit of La Spedla (a subpeak of Piz Bernina), at 4,020 metres (13,190 ft).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] Towns along the river include Bormio, Tirano, Sondrio, Bellagio and Lecco (both on Lake Como), Brivio and Lodi.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The Poschiavino, a tributary, originates in Switzerland and flows through the town of Poschiavo.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The Adda's source is in the Alpisella valley near the head of the Fraele glen, within the Rhaetian Alps.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] Its flow is augmented by several smaller streams near Bormio.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] From there, it flows southwest, then west, through the Valtellina, passing Tirano, where the Poschiavino joins from the right, and Sondrio, where the Mallero joins, also from the right.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] This section of the Adda's course is unusual in Northern Italy, as it flows from east to west.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The river flows into the northern end of Lake Como, contributing significantly to the lake's volume.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] Exiting the lake's southeastern (Lecco) arm, it crosses the Lombardy Plain.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] It receives water from the Brembo and Serio from the left, and ultimately joins the Po.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The Trezzo sull'Adda Bridge, constructed in 1377, had a single arch of 72 metres (236 ft), the longest bridge arch built before the introduction of metal in bridge construction.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The lower course of the Adda historically marked the border between the Republic of Venice and the Duchy of Milan, as established by the Treaty of Lodi in 1454.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] Several significant battles have been fought along its banks, including the Battle of Lodi in 1796, where Napoleon defeated Austrian forces.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/adda-river] The bridgehead at Cassano d'Adda and its surrounding area have also been the site of multiple battles, including one in 1705 involving Prince Eugene of Savoy and the French, and another in 1799 where Alexander Suvorov led his forces across the river.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The Roman Empire had ended up in a difficult situation by the end of the fourth century when the East Roman army suffered a heavy defeat at Adrianople against the Goths in 378.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] After that, a series of civil wars broke out that aggravated the situation.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] In 395 the empire was divided in two and Raetia and Noricum belonged to the western empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] At the end of the fourth century, living conditions for the civilian population north of the Alps were still bearable.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Stilicho's campaign against Alarik in the Gothic War in 403 and the passage of Radagaisus army in 405 had been spared them.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Nevertheless, the population increasingly experienced the adverse consequences of the exhausting wars that the army waged to maintain the Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] To keep the army up to date, units were constantly withdrawn from the border and supplemented with barbaric foederati.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] In addition, the military was a huge cost item for the empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] As a result of the internal conflicts and defensive battles against barbarians, the population experienced an increasing tax burden.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Historians see these deteriorating economic conditions as the main cause of the dissatisfaction that led to the Nori uprising in the years around 430/431.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Heather suggests that the uprising was the same as that of the Bagaudae in Brittany and Spain.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] According to him, it had been nothing more than a decision by the population to organize themselves after the empire had left them to their own devices for more than two decades.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Hydatius calls the invasion of the Juthungen and the revolt of the Nori in a sentence, which may indicate that the raid and revolt took place simultaneously.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The Juthungen were a Germanic tribe living north of the Danube that had made themselves heard before in history.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The last time had been during a raid in 383 under the rule of Emperor Valentinian II.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] In late 429 or early 430, the Juthungi crossed the Danube and invaded the province of Reaetia Segunda.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] As on other occasions in the history of the Roman Empire, the reduction of troops at the border and the invasion of the Vandals in Africa was the most plausible reason for the Juthungi to invade the empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Aetius, appointed *magister equitum praesentalis* since 429 and thus in rank equal to Felix, ended his campaign against the Goths at Arles and put his army into position.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The army he led consisted of his own Hunse *bucellari* and parts of the imperial army the *praesentalis* from Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The later emperor Avitus, and the poet Merobaudes were also part of this army.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] As soon as the Alpine passes were passable, the army headed for Raetia in the north and fought the attackers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] In all likelihood, fights took place naar the city of Augusta Vindelicorum (present-day Augsburg).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] An inscription has been found in this city that is associated with the campaign of Aetius in Raetia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The campaign ended with a quick and complete victory of the Romans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] According to another inscription, Merobaudes distinguished himself in battle.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] He was honored with a statue at the Forum of Trajan.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] It is assumed that Aetius did not chase the retreating Juthungi across the Danube River.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Reports about the bad campaign against the Vandals in Africa forced him to interrupt his campaign.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] He returned with his army to Ravenna for consultation.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] However, the consultation with his colleague *magister militum praesentalis* Felix, about the following strategy led to a crisis.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] According to Wijendaele, the rivalry between Aetius and Felix was the basis for this.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] This one erupted because Aëtius had to give up part of his force before the war against the Vandals.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] There broke out mutiny at this army unit that committed an attack on Felix.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Prosper points to Aëtius as if he had had a hand in this.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] In 431 Aetius resumed his campaign in the northern Alps, this time he deployed his army against the rebellious inhabitants of the province of Noricum.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] According to Wijendaele, he burned the province and returned to Italy loaded with loot.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The games held in Rome in 432 in his honor were financed with this.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] After the fall of Felix, Aëtius has become the most powerful soldier of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Aetius' performance put evil blood on the imperial authority in Ravenna.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The tension between the quirky general and Galla Placidia led her to put all her pawns on Bonifatius and she dropped Aetius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] When Aëtius left Italy in 432 to participate in the war against the Franks, she lets Bonifatius return from Africa and appoints him as her new commander in chief.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Aëtius's reaction is not long in coming and a Roman civil war breaks out between him and Bonifatius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] A number of contemporary historians: Priscus, Prosper, Hydatius report about a campaign against the Juthungi and the Nori in 430 and 431 by Aëtius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Background information about the how and why of this campaign is largely lacking.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] Only Prosper lights up a tip of the veil by telling that there was a conspiracy against Aetius by Felix and Galla Placidia, and that Felix was murdered by Aetius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] The order of the events do not match in the sources.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] In general, more importance is attached to that of Hydatius because he visited Aëtius as an envoy on a diplomatic mission.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] If one maintains the order of Hydatius' events, Aëtius first campaigned against a group of Goths near Arles in the early spring of 430, before targeting the Juthungen and Nori.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/aetius-campaign-in-the-alps] It was only after he had defeated the Goths did Aetius leave for the Alps.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Africa was one of the wealthiest provinces in the Roman Empire, second only to Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] It was said that Africa fed the Roman populace for eight months of the year, while Egypt provided the remaining four months' supply.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The area east of the Fossa Regia was fully Romanized with one third of the population made of Italian colonists and their descendants, the other two thirds were Romanized Berbers, who were all Christians and nearly all Latin speaking.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Rome's first province in North Africa was established by the Roman Republic in 146 BC, following its conquest of Carthage by Scipio Aemilianus in the Third Punic War.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Utica, which had sided with Rome against Carthage, was made the administrative capital.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The remaining territory was left in the domain of the Berber Numidian king Massinissa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] At this time, the Roman policy in Africa appears to have been to prevent a rival great power rising in Western North Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In 118 BC, the Numidian king Micipsa died and split the kingdom among his three heirs: Jugurtha, Hiempsal I and Adherbal.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Hiempsal was assassinated in 117 BC; Adherbal fled to Rome to request protection and the intervention of the Roman Senate.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In 112 BC, Jugurtha resumed the civil war and defeated Adherbal at Cirta, and embarked on the Jugurthine War against Rome (111–106 BC).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Following Jugurtha's defeat, his former territory was placed under the control of the Berber Mauritanian king Bocchus.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] During Caesar's civil war (49–45 BC), Caesar created a new African province, *Africa* *nova,* from territory taken from the Numidians.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The original province was called *Africa vetus*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] During the Second Triumvirate, the two provinces were unified, possibly in 35 BC, in consequence of border conflicts.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Roman governors of the province won three triumphs between 34 and 28 BC.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Further expansion of the province continued under the emperor Augustus, with conflicts recorded through to AD 6.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Under the Augustan constitutional reforms, in 27 BC the region was made a senatorial province, and eventually became known as *Africa proconsularis* (as it was ruled by a senatorial proconsul rather than an imperial legate).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Old Africa (*Africa Vetus*), which generally includes the areas mentioned, was also known by the Romans (Pliny) as *Africa propria*, of which Carthage was the capital.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The region remained part of the Roman empire until the Germanic migrations of the 5th century AD.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The Vandals crossed into Northwest Africa from Spain in AD 429, had conquered the region by AD 439, founding a kingdom which also included Corsica, Sardinia and the Balearics.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The Vandals controlled the country as a warrior-elite but faced strong resistance from the native Berbers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The Vandals also persecuted Chalcedonian Roman Africans and Berbers, as the Vandals were adherents of Arianism (the semi-trinitarian doctrines of Arius, a priest of Egypt).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Towards the end of the 5th century, Vandal control over the area diminished, abandoning most of the interior territories to the Mauri and other Berber tribes of the region.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In AD 533, emperor Justinian, using a Vandal dynastic dispute as pretext, sent an army under the general Belisarius to recover Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In a year-long campaign, Belisarius defeated the Vandals, entered Carthage in triumph and re-established Roman rule over the province.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The restored Roman administration was successful in fending off the attacks of the Amazigh desert tribes, and by means of an extensive fortification network managed to extend its rule once again to the interior.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] From AD 534–91, the northwest African provinces were grouped together with the Byzantine province of Spania into the Praetorian prefecture of Africa, this time separate from Praetorian prefecture of Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In AD 591, this was replaced by emperor Maurice with the Exarchate of Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Heraclius the Elder, the Exarch of Africa, and his son Heraclius, overthrew the emperor Phocas at Constantinople in AD 610.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Heraclius briefly considered moving the imperial capital from Constantinople to Carthage.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Following Heraclius' death in AD 641, the exarchate continued to operate.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In AD 698, the Muslim Umayyad army, under general Hassan ibn al-Nu'man al-Ghassani conquered Carthage and defeated the Exarchate, ending Roman and Christian rule in Northwest Africa and establishing Islamic rule in the region.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Roman 'direct' control, i.e. excluding vassal/client states.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The Roman military presence of Northwest Africa was relatively small, consisting of about 28,000 troops and auxiliaries in Numidia and the two Mauretanian provinces.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Starting in the 2nd century AD, these garrisons were manned mostly by local inhabitants.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] A sizable Latin-speaking population developed that was multinational in background, sharing the northwest African region with those speaking Punic and Berber languages.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Imperial security forces began to be recruited from the local population, including the Berbers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] By the end of the Western Roman Empire nearly all of the Maghreb was fully romanised, according to Mommsen in his *The Provinces of the Roman Empire*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Roman Africans enjoyed a high level of prosperity.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] This prosperity (and romanisation) touched partially even the populations living outside the Roman limes (mainly the Garamantes and the Getuli), who were reached with Roman expeditions to Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The prosperity of most towns depended on agriculture.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Described as the "granary of the empire", it was said that Africa fed the Roman populace for eight months of the year, while Egypt provided the remaining four months' supply.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Northwest Africa, according to one estimate, produced one million tons of cereals each year, one-quarter of which was exported.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Additional crops included beans, figs, grapes, and other fruits.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] By the 2nd century BC, olive oil rivaled cereals as an export item.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Principal production and export goods included textiles, marble, wine, timber, livestock, pottery (such as African Red Slip), and wool, as well as enslaved people, and the capture and transporting of exotic wild animals.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The incorporation of colonial cities into the Roman Empire brought an unparalleled degree of urbanization to vast areas of territory, particularly in Northwest Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] This level of rapid urbanization had a structural impact on the town economy, and artisan production in Roman cities became closely tied to agrarian spheres of production.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] As Rome's population grew, so did the city's demand for Northwest African produce.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] This flourishing trade allowed the Northwest African provinces to increase artisan production in rapidly developing cities, making them highly organized urban centers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Many Roman cities shared both consumer and producer model city aspects, as artisanal activity was directly related to the economic role cities played in long-distance trade networks.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The urban population became increasingly engaged in the craft and service sectors and less in agrarian employment, until a significant portion of the town's vitality came from the sale or trade of products through middlemen to markets in areas both rural and abroad.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The changes that occurred in the infrastructure for agricultural processing, like olive oil and wine production, as trade continued to develop both cities and commerce directly influenced the volume of artisan production.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The scale, quality, and demand for these products reached its acme in Roman Northwest Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The Northwest African provinces spanned across regions rich with olive plantations and potters' clay sources, which led to the early development of fine Ancient Roman pottery, especially African Red Slip *terra sigillata* tableware and clay oil lamp manufacture, as a crucial industry.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Lamps provided the most common form of artificial illumination in Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] They were used for public and private lighting, as votive offerings in temples, lighting at festivals, and as grave goods.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] As the craft developed and increased in quality and craftsmanship, the Northwest African creations began to rival their Italian and Grecian models and eventually surpassed them in merit and in demand.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The innovative use of molds around the 1st century BC allowed workshops to produce pottery in a greater variety of shapes and decorative styles.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The skill of the lamp maker was demonstrated by the quality of decoration typically found on the flat top of the lamp, or discus, and the outer rim, or shoulder.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The production process took several stages.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Decorative motifs were created using small individual molds, and were then added as appliqué to the plain archetype of the lamp.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The embellished lamp was then used to make two plaster half-molds: one lower half and one upper half mold.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Using this pair of molds, multiple copies could be mass-produced.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Decorative motifs varied depending on the lamp's function and popular taste.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Ornate patterning of squares and circles was later added to the shoulder with a stylus, as well as palm trees, small fish, animals, and flower patterns.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The discus was reserved for conventional scenes of gods, goddesses, mythological subjects, scenes from daily life, erotic scenes, and natural images.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] In post-Roman instances of Northwest African lamps, Christian influences also appear, with images of saints, crosses, and biblical figures becoming commonly used motifs.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Traditional mythological symbols continued to remain popular as well, some of which may be traced back to the Punic period.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Artisanal, political, and social disruption in the 3rd century AD led to a decrease in the production of ceramic goods in North Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Afterwards, lamp-making revived and accelerated.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The introduction of fine local red-fired clays in the late 4th century AD triggered this revival.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] African Red Slip ware (ARS), or African Terra Sigillata, revolutionized the pottery and lamp-making industry.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] ARS ware was produced from the last third of the 1st century AD onwards, and was of major importance in the mid-to-late Roman periods.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Famous in antiquity as "fine" or high-quality tableware, it was distributed both regionally and throughout the Mediterranean basin along well-established and heavily trafficked trade routes.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Northwest Africa's economy flourished as its products were dispersed and demand for its products dramatically increased.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Initially, the ARS lamp designs imitated the simple design of 3rd- to 4th-century coarseware lamps, often with globules on the shoulder or with fluted walls.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] More ornate designs appeared before the early 5th century as demand spurred on the creative process.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The development and widespread distribution of ARS finewares marks the most distinctive phase of Northwest African pottery-making.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] These characteristic pottery lamps were produced in large quantities by efficiently organized production centers with large-scale manufacturing abilities.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] They can be attributed to specific pottery-making centers in northern and central Tunisia by way of chemical analysis, allowing archeologists to trace distribution patterns from their source through the regions and across the Mediterranean.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Some major ARS centers in central Tunisia are Sidi Marzouk Tounsi, Henchir el-Guellal (Djilma), and Henchir es-Srira, all of which have ARS lamp artifacts attributed to them by the microscopic chemical makeup of the clay fabric as well as macroscopic style prevalent in that region.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Regional pottery markets fueled the economy of both urban and rural sites and supported markets abroad.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Certain vessel forms, fabrics, and decorative techniques like rouletting, appliqué, and stamped décor, are specific for a certain region and even for a certain pottery center.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] If neither form nor decoration of the material is identifiable, it is possible to trace an item using chemical analysis, not just to a certain region but even to its place of production by comparing its makeup to a matrix of important northeastern and central Tunisian potteries.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Pine forests, with a herb layer of grasses, were widespread and economically significant, especially in the humid zone, the northeast of modern Tunisia (the areas known as the Tell and parts of the Dorsal mountains).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Many areas are described as *saltus*, land used for non-agricultural exploitation.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Timber, pitch (used to line amphorae and waterproof ships), firewood, pine nuts, and charcoal would all have been produced.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Grazing was also practiced on forested land.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] Olive plantations were also widespread, usually on land previously forested, and the pomace residue after oil extraction was also locally important as fuel.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/africa-roman-province] The temple of Mercury Silvius, a god of commerce related to forests, in Dougga, and many lesser monuments elsewhere, are evidence of the importance of forests to local trade.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The **Alans** (Latin: *Alani*) were an ancient and medieval Iranic nomadic pastoral people who migrated to what is today the North Caucasus; some continued on to Europe and later North Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] They are generally regarded as part of the Sarmatians, and possibly related to the Massagetae.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Modern historians have connected the Alans with the Central Asian Yancai of Chinese sources and with the Aorsi of Roman sources.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Having migrated westwards and becoming dominant among the Sarmatians on the Pontic–Caspian steppe, the Alans are mentioned by Roman sources in the 1st century CE.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] At that time they had settled in the region north of the Black Sea and frequently raided the Parthian Empire and the South Caucasus provinces of the Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Between 215 and 250 CE the Goths broke their hold on the Pontic Steppe, thereby assimilating a significant population of associated Alans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] After the Hunnic defeat of the Goths on the Pontic Steppe around 375 CE, many of the Alans along with various Germanic tribes migrated westwards.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] They crossed the Rhine in 406 CE along with the Vandals and Suebi, settling in Orléans and Valence.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Around 409 CE they joined the Vandals and Suebi in crossing the Pyrenees into the Iberian Peninsula, settling in Lusitania and Hispania Carthaginensis.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Iberian Alans, soundly defeated by the Visigoths in 418 CE, subsequently surrendered their autonomy to the Hasdingi Vandals.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 428 CE, the Vandals and Alans crossed the Strait of Gibraltar into North Africa, where they founded a kingdom which lasted until its conquest by Byzantine emperor Justinian I in 534 CE.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Eventually in the 9th century, those Alans who remained under Hunnic rule established the kingdom of Alania, a regional power in the Northern Caucasus.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It survived until the Mongol invasions of the 13th century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Various scholars consider these Alans to be the ancestors of the modern Ossetians.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans spoke an Eastern Iranian language which derived from Scytho-Sarmatian; in turn, the language evolved into the modern Ossetian language.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The name *Alan* represents an Eastern Iranian dialectal form of the Old Iranian term *Aryan*, and so is cognate with the name of the country *Īrān* (from the gen. plur.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Rarer Latin spellings include *Alauni* or *Halani*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The name was also preserved in the modern Ossetian language as *Allon*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The ethnonym *Alān* is a dialectal variant of the Old Iranian **Aryāna*, itself derived from the root *arya*-, meaning 'Aryan', the common self-designation of Indo-Iranian peoples.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It probably came in use in the early history of the Alans for the purpose of uniting a heterogeneous group of tribes through the invocation of a common, ancestral 'Aryan' origin.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Like the name of Iran (**Aryānām*), the adjective **aryāna* is related to *Airyanəm Waēǰō* ('stretch of the Aryas'), the mythical homeland of the early Iranians mentioned in the *Avesta*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Some other ethnonyms also bear the name of the Alans: the *Rhoxolāni* ('Bright Alans'), an offshoot of the Alans whose name may be linked to religious practices, and the *Alanorsoi* ('White Alans'), perhaps a conglomerate of Alans and Aorsi.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The personal names *Alan* and *Alain* (from Latin *Alanus*) may have been introduced by Alan settlers to Western Europe during the first millennium.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans were also known over the course of their history by another group of related names including the variations *Asi*, *As*, and *Os* (Romanian **Iasi or Olani**, Bulgarian **Uzi**, Hungarian **Jász**, Russian **Jasy**, Georgian **Osi**).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It is this name at the root of the modern *Ossetian*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans were famed for their elite and highly mobile cavalry, a fighting style they inherited from their Sarmatian relatives.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans' influence on mounted warfare was widespread, with their tactics and equipment impacting the Roman and Germanic armies, among others.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Alani boys learned to ride at a young age, and Roman writer Ammianus Marcellinus remarked that walking was considered offensive for an Alanic man.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] A hallmark Alanic tactic, the feigned retreat was designed to draw enemy infantry into a vulnerable position.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Alani horsemen would pretend to flee before suddenly wheeling around to attack the enemy's exposed flank.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] As mercenaries for the Romans and other powers, the Alans demonstrated a sophisticated understanding of combined-arms tactics.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Their missile-equipped cavalry would harry the enemy, pinning them in place before the shock cavalry delivered a devastating charge.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Alani cavalry was highly mobile and was used for rapid skirmishing and opportunistic attacks against enemy flanks.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The mobility of their cavalry and the psychological terror they inspired in less disciplined infantry were major advantages.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans were recruited into the Mongol forces and known as the Asud, with one unit called "Right Alan Guard" that was combined with "recently surrendered" soldiers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans were formed out of the merger of the Massagetae, a Central Asian Iranian nomadic people, with some old tribal groups.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The first mentions of names that historians link with the *Alani* appear at almost the same time in texts from the Mediterranean, Middle East and China.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In the 1st century, the Alans migrated westwards from Central Asia, achieving a dominant position among the Sarmatians living between the Don River and the Caspian Sea.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans are mentioned in the Vologases inscription which reads that Vologases I, the Parthian king between around 45 and 78, in the 11th year of his reign (62), battled Kuluk, king of the Alani.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The 1st century Jewish historian Josephus supplements this inscription.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Josephus reports in the *Jewish Wars* (book 7, ch.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The fact that the Alans invaded Parthia through Hyrcania shows that at the time many Alans were still based north-east of the Caspian Sea.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] By the early 2nd century the Alans were in firm control of the Lower Volga and Kuban.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] These lands had earlier been occupied by the Aorsi and the Siraces, whom the Alans apparently absorbed, dispersed and/or destroyed, since they were no longer mentioned in contemporaneous accounts.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It is likely that the Alans' influence stretched further westwards, encompassing most of the Sarmatian world, which by then possessed a relatively homogenous culture.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 135 CE, the Alans made a huge raid into Asia Minor via the Caucasus, ravaging Media and Armenia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] They were eventually driven back by Arrian, the governor of Cappadocia, who wrote a detailed report (*Ektaxis kata Alanoon* or 'War Against the Alans') that is a major source for studying Roman military tactics.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] From 215 to 250, the Germanic Goths expanded south-eastwards and broke the Alan dominance on the Pontic Steppe.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans however seem to have had a significant influence on the culture of the Goths, who became excellent horsemen and adopted the Alanic animal style art.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] After the Gothic entry to the steppe, many of the Alans seem to have retreated eastwards towards the Don, where they seem to have established contacts with the Huns.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Ammianus writes that the Alans were "somewhat like the Huns, but in their manner of life and their habits they are less savage." Jordanes contrasted them with the Huns, noting that the Alans "were their equals in battle, but unlike them in their civilisation, manners and appearance".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In the late 4th century, Vegetius conflates Alans and Huns in his military treatise – *Hunnorum Alannorumque natio*, the "nation of Huns and Alans" – and collocates Goths, Huns and Alans, *exemplo Gothorum et Alannorum Hunnorumque*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The 4th century Roman historian Ammianus Marcellinus noted that the Alans were "formerly called Massagetae," while Dio Cassius wrote that "they are Massagetae." It is likely that the Alans were an amalgamation of various Iranian peoples, including Sarmatians, Massagetae and Sakas.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Scholars have connected the Alans to the nomadic state of Yancai mentioned in Chinese sources.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Yancai are first mentioned in connection with late 2nd century BC diplomat Zhang Qian's travels in Chapter 123 of *Shiji* (whose author, Sima Qian, died c.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Yancai of Chinese records has again been equated with the Aorsi, a powerful Sarmatian tribe living between the Don River and the Aral Sea, mentioned in Roman records, in particular Strabo.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Later Han dynasty Chinese chronicle, the *Hou Hanshu*, 88 (covering the period 25–220 and completed in the 5th century), mentioned a report that the *Yancai* nation (奄蔡 lit "Vast Steppes" or "Extensive Grasslands" < LHC **ʔɨamB*-*sɑC*; a.k.a.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Zadneprovskiy suggests that the Kangju subjugation of Yancai occurred in the 1st century BC, and that this subjugation caused various Sarmatian tribes, including the Aorsi, to migrate westwards, which played a major role in starting the Migration Period.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The 3rd century Weilüe also notes that Yancai was then known to be Alans, although they were no longer vassals of the Kangju.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Around 370, according to Ammianus, the peaceful relations between the Alans and Huns were broken, after the Huns attacked the Don Alans, killing many of them and establishing an alliance with the survivors.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] These Alans successfully invaded the Goths in 375 together with the Huns.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] They subsequently accompanied the Huns in their westward expansion.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Following the Hunnic invasion in 370, other Alans, along with other Sarmatians, migrated westward.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] One of these Alan groups fought together with the Goths in the decisive Battle of Adrianople in 378 CE, in which emperor Valens was killed.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] As the Roman Empire continued to decline, the Alans split into various groups; some fought for the Romans while others joined the Huns, Visigoths or Ostrogoths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] A portion of the western Alans joined the Vandals and the Suebi in their invasion of Roman Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Gregory of Tours mentions in his *Liber historiae Francorum* ("Book of Frankish History") that the Alan king Respendial saved the day for the Vandals in an armed encounter with the Franks at the crossing of the Rhine on 31 December 406.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] According to Gregory, another group of Alans, led by Goar, crossed the Rhine at the same time, but immediately joined the Romans and settled in Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Under Beorgor (*Beorgor rex Alanorum*), they moved throughout Gaul, till the reign of Petronius Maximus, when they crossed the Alps in the winter of 464, into Liguria, but were there defeated, and Beorgor slain, by Ricimer, commander of the Emperor's forces.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Goar settled a substantial number of his followers in the Orleanais and the area to the north and personally moved his own capital to the city of Orleans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Under Goar, they allied with the Burgundians led by Gundaharius, with whom they installed the Emperor Jovinus as usurper.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Under Goar's successor Sangiban, the Alans of Orléans played a critical role in repelling the invasion of Attila the Hun at the Battle of Châlons.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 463 the Alans defeated the Goths at the battle of Orléans, and they later defeated the Franks led by Childeric in 466.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Around 502–503 Clovis attacked Armorica but was defeated by the Alans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] However, the Alans, who were Chalcedonian Christians like Clovis, desired cordial relations with him to counterbalance the hostile Arian Visigoths who coveted the land north of the Loire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Therefore, an accord was arranged by which Clovis came to rule the various peoples of Armorica and the military strength of the area was integrated into the Merovingian military.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Following the fortunes of the Vandals and Suebi into the Iberian Peninsula (Hispania, comprising modern Portugal and Spain) in 409, the Alans led by Respendial settled in the provinces of Lusitania and Carthaginensis.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Kingdom of the Alans was among the first Barbarian kingdoms to be founded.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Siling Vandals settled in Baetica, the Suebi in coastal Gallaecia, and the Asding Vandals in the rest of Gallaecia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Although the newcomers controlled Hispania they were still a tiny minority among a larger Hispano-Roman population, approximately 200,000 out of 6,000,000.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 418 (or 426 according to some authors), the Alan king, Attaces, was killed in battle against the Visigoths, and this branch of the Alans subsequently appealed to the Asding Vandal king Gunderic to accept the Alan crown.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The separate ethnic identity of Respendial's Alans dissolved.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Although some of these Alans are thought to have remained in Iberia, most went to North Africa with the Vandals in 429.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Later the rulers of the Vandal Kingdom in North Africa styled themselves *Rex Wandalorum et Alanorum* ("King of the Vandals and Alans").
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In the Iberian peninsula the Alans settled in Lusitania (Alentejo) and the Cartaginense provinces.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] They became known in retrospect for their massive hunting and fighting running mastiff-type dogs, the Alaunt, which they apparently introduced to Europe.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The breed is extinct, but its name is carried by a Spanish breed of dog still called *Alano*, traditionally used in boar hunting and cattle herding.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alano name, however, has historically been used for a number of dog breeds in a few European countries thought to descend from the original dog of the Alans, such as the German mastiff (Great Dane) and the French Dogue de Bordeaux, among others.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Y-DNA consistent with the Alans can still be found in these regions, mainly around the District of Portalegre.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans who remained in their original area of settlement north of the Caucasus (and for a time east of the Caspian Sea as well), came into contact and conflict with the Bulgars, the Gökturks, and the Khazars, who drove most of them from the plains and into the mountains.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans converted to Byzantine Orthodoxy in the first quarter of the 10th century, during the patriarchate of Nicholas I Mystikos.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Al-Mas‘udi reports that they apostasized in 932, but this seems to have been short-lived.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans are collectively mentioned as Byzantine-rite Christians in the 13th century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Caucasian Alans were the ancestors of the modern Ossetians, whose ethnonym derives from the name *Ās* (very probably the ancient *Aorsi*; al-Ma'sudi mentions *al-Arsiyya* as guards among the Khazars, and the Rus' called the Alans *Yasi*), a sister tribe of the Alans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The *Armenian Geography* uses the name *Ashtigor* for the most westerly located Alans, a name which survives as *Digor* and still refers to the western division of the Ossetians.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Furthermore, in Ossetian, *Asi* refers to the region around Mount Elbrus, where they probably formerly lived.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In the territory from Urukh to Mount Elbrus, a sufficient number of Ossetian toponyms have been preserved up until the 20th century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Some of the other Alans remained under the rule of the Huns.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Those of the eastern division, though dispersed about the steppes until late medieval times, were forced by the Mongols into the Caucasus, where they remain as the Ossetians.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Between the 9th and 12th centuries, they formed a network of tribal alliances that gradually evolved into the Christian kingdom of Alania.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Most Alans submitted to the Mongol Empire in 1239–1277.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] They participated in Mongol invasions of Europe and the Song dynasty in Southern China, and the Battle of Kulikovo under Mamai of the Golden Horde.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 1253, the Franciscan friar William of Rubruck reported numerous Europeans in Central Asia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It is also known that 30,000 Alans formed the royal guard (Asud) of the Yuan court in Dadu (Beijing).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Marco Polo later reported their role in the Yuan dynasty in his book *Il Milione*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It is said that those Alans contributed to a modern Mongol clan, Asud.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] John of Montecorvino, archbishop of Dadu (Khanbaliq), reportedly converted many Alans to Roman Catholic Christianity in addition to Armenians in China.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In Poland and Lithuania, Alans were also part of the powerful Clan of Ostoja.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] This twelve-year-long siege is not found in any other report, however the Russian historian A.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Krasnov connected this battle with two Chechen folktales he recorded in 1967 that spoke of an old hunter named Idig who with his companions defended the Dakuoh mountain for 12 years against Tatar-Mongols.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Against the Alans and the Cumans (Kipchaks), the Mongols used divide-and-conquer tactics by first telling the Cumans to stop allying with the Alans and, after the Cumans followed their suggestion, the Mongols then attacked the Cumans after defeating the Alans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Alan and Kipchak guards were used by Kublai Khan.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 1368 at the end of the Yuan dynasty in China Toghan Temür was accompanied by his faithful Alan guards.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Mangu enlisted in his bodyguard half the troops of the Alan prince, Arslan, whose younger son Nicholas took a part in the expedition of the Mongols against Karajang (Yunnan).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] This Alan imperial guard was still in existence in 1272, 1286 and 1309, and it was divided into two corps with headquarters in the Ling pei province (Karakorúm).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The French-Flemish friar and traveler William of Rubruck mentions Alans numerous times in the account of his 1253–1255 journey through Eurasia to the Great Khan, e.g.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Alans living as Mongol subjects in Crimea, Old Astrakhan, the Khan's capital Karakorum, and also still as freemen in their Caucasian homeland ("the Alans or Aas, who are Christians and still fight the Tartars").
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alan guards converted to Catholicism as reported by Odorico.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 1277 Mengu-Timur sent an expedition against the rebellious Alans in the city of Dedyakov.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] As a result of the campaign, the city was burned.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] According to many researchers, Dedyakov was located on the territory of the capital of North Ossetia - Vladikavkaz.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It is believed that some Alans resettled to the North (Barsils), merging with Volga Bulgars and Burtas, eventually transforming to Volga Tatars.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It is supposed that the Iasians, a group of Alans founded a market in the northeast of Romania (about 1200–1300), near the Prut river, later called Iași town.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The latter became the capital of Moldavia in the Middle Ages.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Classical Alania finally ceased to exist at the end of the 14th century, when Tamerlane invaded.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] After defeating the Golden Horde in the Battle of the Terek River in 1395, he subsequently attacked several Alanians leaders, leading to months of slaughter and enslavement, which are still remembered in a popular Ossetian folk song called "mother of Zadaleska".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Tamerlane's invasion led to the Alans fleeing into the depths of the Caucasus Mountains and the end of the Alans' presence in the steppes north of the Caucasus, which is preserved in the Digorian legends.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Alan mercenaries were involved in the affair with the Catalan Company.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Ilyinskyon on bone fragments from 10 Alanic burials on the Don River, DNA could be abstracted from a total of seven.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Four of them turned out to belong to yDNA Haplogroup G2 and six of them had mtDNA I.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The fact that many of the samples share the same y- and mtDNA raises the possibility that the tested individuals belonged to the same tribe or even were close relatives.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Nevertheless this supports the argument for a direct Alan ancestry of Ossetians, competing with the hypothesis that Ossetians are alanized Caucasic-speakers, as the main haplogroup among Ossetians is also G2.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In 2015, the Institute of Archaeology in Moscow conducted research on various Sarmato-Alan and Saltovo-Mayaki culture Kurgan burials.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In this analysis, the two Alan samples from the 4th to 6th century had yDNAs G2a-P15 and R1a-z94, while from the three Sarmatian samples from 2nd to 3rd century two had yDNA J1-M267 and one possessed R1a.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Also, the three Saltovo-Mayaki samples from 8th to 9th century turned out to have yDNAs G, J2a-M410 and R1a-z94 respectively.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] A genetic study published in *Nature* in May 2018 examined the remains of six Alans buried in the Caucasus from c.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The sample of Y-DNA extracted belonged to haplogroup R1 and haplogroup Q-M242.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] One of the Q-M242 samples found in Beslan, North Ossetia from 200 found 4 relatives among Chechens from the Shoanoy Teip.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The samples of mtDNA extracted belonged to HV2a1, U4d3, X2f, H13a2c, H5, and W1.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Archaeological finds support the written sources.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Rau (1927) first identified late Sarmatian sites with the historical Alans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Based on the archaeological material, they were one of the Iranian-speaking nomadic tribes that began to enter the Sarmatian area between the middle of the 1st and the 2nd centuries.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] The Alans' language, Alanic, was in use for about 12 centuries and used the Greek alphabet.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Byzantine Greek sources only recorded small samples.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Prior to their Christianisation, the Alans were Indo-Iranian polytheists, subscribing either to the poorly understood Scythian pantheon or to a polytheistic form of Zoroastrianism.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Some traditions were directly inherited from the Scythians, like embodying their dominant god in elaborate rituals.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In the 4th–5th centuries the Alans were at least partially Christianized by Byzantine Arian missionaries of the church.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] By the 13th century, most of the urban population of Ossetia gradually became Eastern Orthodox Christian as a result of Georgian missionary work.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] In the 13th century, invading Mongol hordes pushed the eastern Alans further south into the Caucasus, where they mixed with native Caucasian groups and successively formed three territorial entities each with different developments.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] Around 1395, Timur's army invaded the Northern Caucasus and massacred much of the Alanian population.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] As time went by, Digor in the west came under Kabard and Islamic influence.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] It was through the Kabardians (an East Circassian tribe) that Islam was introduced into the region in the 17th century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] After 1767, all of Alania came under Russian rule, which strengthened Orthodox Christianity in that region considerably.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alans] A substantial minority of today's Ossetians are followers of the traditional Ossetian religion, revived in the 1980s as Assianism (Ossetian: *Uatsdin* – 'True Faith').
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric began his career under the Gothic soldier Gainas and later joined the Roman army.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Once an ally of Rome under the Roman emperor Theodosius, Alaric helped defeat the Franks and other allies of a would-be Roman usurper.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Despite losing many thousands of his men, he received little recognition from Rome and left the Roman army disappointed.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] After the death of Theodosius and the disintegration of the Roman armies in 395, he is described as king of the Visigoths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] As the leader of the only effective field force remaining in the Balkans, he sought Roman legitimacy, never quite achieving a position acceptable to himself or to the Roman authorities.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He operated mainly against the successive Western Roman regimes, and marched into Italy, where he died.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He is responsible for the sack of Rome in 410; one of several notable events in the Western Roman Empire's eventual decline.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] According to Jordanes, a 6th-century Roman writer of Gothic origin, Alaric was born on Peuce Island in the Danube Delta in present-day Romania and belonged to the noble Balti dynasty of the Thervingian Goths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Historian Douglas Boin does not make such an unequivocal assessment about Alaric's Gothic heritage and instead claims he came from either the Thervingi or the Greuthung tribes.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] When the Goths suffered setbacks against the Huns, they made a mass migration across the Danube, and fought a war with Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric was probably a child during this period who grew up along Rome's periphery.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric's childhood in the Balkans, where the Goths had settled by way of an agreement with Emperor Theodosius, was spent in the company of veterans who had fought at the Battle of Adrianople in 378, during which they had annihilated much of the Eastern army and killed Emperor Valens.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Imperial campaigns against the Visigoths were conducted until a treaty was reached in 382.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] This treaty was the first *foedus* on imperial Roman soil and required these semi-autonomous Germanic tribes—among whom Alaric was raised—to supply troops for the Roman army in exchange for peace, control of cultivatable land, and freedom from Roman direct administrative control.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Correspondingly, there was hardly a region along the Roman frontier during Alaric's day without Gothic slaves and servants of one form or another.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] For several subsequent decades, many Goths like Alaric were "called up into regular units of the eastern field army" while others served as auxiliaries in campaigns led by Theodosius against the western usurpers Magnus Maximus and Eugenius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] A new phase in the relationship between the Goths and the empire resulted from the treaty signed in 382, as more and more Goths attained aristocratic rank from their service in the imperial army.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric began his military career under the Gothic soldier Gainas, and later joined the Roman army.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He first appeared as leader of a mixed band of Goths and allied peoples, who invaded Thrace in 391 but were stopped by the half-Vandal, Roman general Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] While the Roman poet Claudian belittled Alaric as "a little-known menace" terrorizing southern Thrace during this time, Alaric's abilities and forces were formidable enough to prevent the Roman Emperor Theodosius from crossing the Hebrus River.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] By 392, Alaric had entered Roman military service, which coincided with a reduction of hostilities between Goths and Romans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] In 394, he led a Gothic force that helped Emperor Theodosius defeat the Frankish usurper Arbogast—fighting at the behest of Eugenius—at the Battle of Frigidus.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Despite sacrificing around 10,000 of his men, who had been victims of Theodosius' callous tactical decision to overwhelm the enemies' front lines using Gothic *foederati*, Alaric received little recognition from the emperor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric was among the few who survived the protracted and bloody affair.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Many Romans considered it their "gain" and a victory that so many Goths had died during the Battle of Frigidus River.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric biographer Douglas Boin (2020) posited that seeing ten thousand of his (Alaric's) dead kinsmen likely elicited questions about what kind of ruler Theodosius actually had been and whether remaining in direct Roman service was best for men like him.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Refused the reward he expected, which included a promotion to the position of magister militum and command of regular Roman units, Alaric mutinied and began to march against Constantinople.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] On 17 January 395, Theodosius died of an illness, leaving his two young and incapable sons Arcadius and Honorius in Stilicho's guardianship.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Modern writers regard Alaric as king of the Visigoths from 395.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] According to historian Peter Heather, it is not entirely clear in the sources if Alaric rose to prominence at the time the Goths revolted following Theodosius's death, or if he had already risen within his tribe as early as the war against Eugenius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Whether or not Alaric was a member of an ancient Germanic royal clan—as claimed by Jordanes and debated by historians—is less important than his emergence as a leader, the first of his kind since Fritigern.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Theodosius's death left the Roman field armies collapsing and the Empire divided again between his two sons, one taking the eastern and the other the western portion of the Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho made himself master of the West and attempted to establish control in the East as well, and led an army into Greece.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Historian Roger Collins points out that while the rivalries created by the two halves of the Empire vying for power worked to Alaric's advantage and that of his people, simply being called to authority by the Gothic people did not solve the practicalities of their needs for survival.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He needed Roman authority in order to be supplied by Roman cities.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric took his Gothic army on what Stilicho's propagandist Claudian described as a "pillaging campaign" that began first in the East.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Historian Thomas Burns's interpretation is that Alaric and his men were recruited by Rufinus's Eastern regime in Constantinople, and sent to Thessaly to stave off Stilicho's threat.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric's forces made their way down to Athens and along the coast, where he sought to force a new peace upon the Romans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] In 396, he marched through Thermopylae and sacked Athens, where archaeological evidence shows widespread damage to the city.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Zosimus adds that Stilicho's troops destroyed and pillaged too, and let Alaric's men escape with their plunder.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho was forced to send some of his Eastern forces home.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] They went to Constantinople under the command of one Gainas, a Goth with a large Gothic following.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] On arrival, Gainas murdered Rufinus, and was appointed magister militum for Thrace by Eutropius, the new supreme minister and the only eunuch consul of Rome, who, Zosimus claims, controlled Arcadius "as if he were a sheep".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] A poem by Synesius advises Arcadius to display manliness and remove a "skin-clad savage" (probably referring to Alaric) from the councils of power and his barbarians from the Roman army.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] We do not know if Arcadius ever became aware of this advice, but it had no recorded effect.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho obtained a few more troops from the German frontier and continued to campaign indecisively against the Eastern empire; again he was opposed by Alaric and his men.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] During the next year, 397, Eutropius personally led his troops to victory over some Huns who were marauding in Asia Minor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] With his position thus strengthened he declared Stilicho a public enemy, and he established Alaric as *magister militum per Illyricum* Alaric thus acquired entitlement to gold and grain for his followers and negotiations were underway for a more permanent settlement.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho's supporters in Milan were outraged at this seeming betrayal; meanwhile, Eutropius was celebrated in 398 by a parade through Constantinople for having achieved victory over the "wolves of the North".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric's people were relatively quiet for the next couple of years.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] The new Eastern regime now felt that they could dispense with Alaric's services and they nominally transferred Alaric's province to the West.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] This administrative change removed Alaric's Roman rank and his entitlement to legal provisioning for his men, leaving his army—the only significant force in the ravaged Balkans—as a problem for Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] According to historian Michael Kulikowski, sometime in the spring of 402 Alaric decided to invade Italy, but no sources from antiquity indicate to what purpose.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Burns suggests that Alaric was probably desperate for provisions.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Using Claudian as his source, historian Guy Halsall reports that Alaric's attack actually began in late 401, but since Stilicho was in *Raetia* "dealing with frontier issues" the two did not first confront one another in Italy until 402.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric's entry into Italy followed the route identified in the poetry of Claudian, as he crossed the peninsula's Alpine frontier near the city of Aquileia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] For a period of six to nine months, there were reports of Gothic attacks along the northern Italian roads, where Alaric was spotted by Roman townspeople.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Along the route on *Via Postumia*, Alaric first encountered Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] The first was at Pollentia on Easter Sunday, where Stilicho (according to Claudian) achieved an impressive victory, taking Alaric's wife and children prisoner, and more significantly, seizing much of the treasure that Alaric had amassed over the previous five years' worth of plundering.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Pursuing the retreating forces of Alaric, Stilicho offered to return the prisoners but was refused.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] The second battle was at Verona, where Alaric was defeated for a second time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho once again offered Alaric a truce and allowed him to withdraw from Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Kulikowski explains this confusing, if not outright conciliatory behavior by stating, "given Stilicho's cold war with Constantinople, it would have been foolish to destroy as biddable and violent a potential weapon as Alaric might well prove to be".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Halsall's observations are similar, as he contends that the Roman general's "decision to permit Alaric's withdrawal into *Pannonia* makes sense if we see Alaric's force entering Stilicho's service, and Stilicho's victory being less total than Claudian would have us believe".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Perhaps more revealing is a report from the Greek historian Zosimus—writing a half a century later—that indicates an agreement was concluded between Stilicho and Alaric in 405, which suggests Alaric being in "western service at that point", likely stemming from arrangements made back in 402.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Between 404 and 405, Alaric remained in one of the four *Pannonian* provinces, from where he could "play East off against West while potentially threatening both".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Although the imperial government was struggling to muster enough troops to contain these barbarian invasions, Stilicho managed to stifle the threat posed by the tribes under Radagaisus, when the latter split his forces into three separate groups.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho cornered Radagaisus near Florence and starved the invaders into submission.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Meanwhile, Alaric—bestowed with codicils of *magister militum* by Stilicho and now supplied by the West—awaited for one side or the other to incite him to action as Stilicho faced further difficulties from more barbarians.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Sometime in 406 and into 407, more large groups of barbarians, consisting primarily of Vandals, Sueves and Alans, crossed the Rhine into Gaul while about the same time a rebellion occurred in Britain.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Under a common soldier named Constantine it spread to Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Burdened by so many enemies, Stilicho's position was strained.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] During this crisis in 407, Alaric again marched on Italy, taking a position in Noricum (modern Austria), where he demanded a sum of 4,000 pounds of gold to buy off another full-scale invasion.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] The Roman Senate loathed the idea of supporting Alaric; Zosimus observed that one senator famously declaimed *Non est ista pax, sed pactio servitutis* ("This is not peace, but a pact of servitude").
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho paid Alaric the 4,000 pounds of gold nevertheless.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] This agreement, sensible in view of the military situation, fatally weakened Stilicho's standing at Honorius's court.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Twice Stilicho had allowed Alaric to escape his grasp, and Radagaisus had advanced all the way to the outskirts of Florence.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] In the East, Arcadius died on 1 May 408 and was replaced by his son Theodosius II; Stilicho seems to have planned to march to Constantinople, and to install there a regime loyal to himself.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He may also have intended to give Alaric a senior official position and send him against the rebels in Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Before Stilicho could do so, while he was away at Ticinum at the head of a small detachment, a bloody coup against his supporters took place at Honorius's court.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] It was led by Honorius's minister, Olympius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho's small escort of Goths and Huns was commanded by a Goth, Sarus, whose Gothic troops massacred the Hun contingent in their sleep, and then withdrew towards the cities in which their own families were billeted.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Stilicho ordered that Sarus's Goths should not be admitted, but, now without an army, he was forced to flee for sanctuary.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Agents of Olympius promised Stilicho his life, but instead betrayed and killed him.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric was again declared an enemy of the emperor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Olympius's men then massacred the families of the federate troops (as presumed supporters of Stilicho, although they had probably rebelled against him), and the troops defected *en masse* to Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Many thousands of barbarian auxiliaries, along with their wives and children, joined Alaric in Noricum.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] The conspirators seem to have let their main army disintegrate and had no policy except hunting down supporters of Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Italy was left without effective indigenous defence forces thereafter.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] As a declared 'enemy of the emperor', Alaric was denied the legitimacy that he needed to collect taxes and hold cities without large garrisons, which he could not afford to detach.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He again offered to move his men, this time to Pannonia, in exchange for a modest sum of money and the modest title of Comes, but he was refused because Olympius's regime regarded him as a supporter of Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] When Alaric was rebuffed, he led his force of around 30,000 men—many newly enlisted and understandably motivated—on a march toward Rome to avenge their murdered families.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] He moved across the Julian Alps into Italy, probably using the route and supplies arranged for him by Stilicho, bypassing the imperial court in Ravenna which was protected by widespread marshland and had a port, and in September 408 he menaced the city of Rome, imposing a strict blockade.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] No blood was shed this time; Alaric relied on hunger as his most powerful weapon.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric also recruited some 40,000 freed Gothic slaves.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Thus ended Alaric's first siege of Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] After having provisionally agreed to the terms offered by Alaric for lifting the blockade, Honorius recanted; historian A.D.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Lee highlights that one of the points of contention for the emperor was Alaric's expectation of being named head of the Roman Army, a post Honorius was not prepared to grant to Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] When this title was not bestowed onto Alaric, he proceeded to not only "besiege Rome again in late 409, but also to proclaim a leading senator, Priscus Attalus, as a rival emperor, from whom Alaric then received the appointment" he desired.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Meanwhile, Alaric's newly appointed "emperor" Attalus, who seems not to have understood the limits of his power or his dependence on Alaric, failed to take Alaric's advice and lost the grain supply in Africa to a pro-Honorian *comes Africae*, Heraclian.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Then, sometime in 409, Attalus—accompanied by Alaric—marched on Ravenna and after receiving unprecedented terms and concessions from the legitimate emperor Honorius, refused him and instead demanded that Honorius be deposed and exiled.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Fearing for his safety, Honorius made preparations to flee to Ravenna when ships carrying 4,000 troops arrived from Constantinople, restoring his resolve.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Now that Honorius no longer felt the need to negotiate, Alaric (regretting his choice of puppet emperor) deposed Attalus, perhaps to re-open negotiations with Ravenna.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Negotiations with Honorius might have succeeded had it not been for another intervention by Sarus, of the Amal family, and therefore a hereditary enemy of Alaric and his house.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Why Sarus, who had been in imperial service for years under Stilicho, acted at this moment remains a mystery, but Alaric interpreted this attack as directed by Ravenna and as bad faith from Honorius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] No longer would negotiations suffice for Alaric, as his patience had reached its end, which led him to march on Rome for a third and final time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] On 24 August 410, Alaric and his forces began the sack of Rome, an assault that lasted three days.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Jerome (Letter 127.12, to the lady *Principia*) lamented: "A dreadful rumour reached us from the West.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] When liturgical vessels were taken from the basilica of St.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Peter and Alaric heard of this, he ordered them returned and had them ceremoniously restored in the church.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] According to historian Patrick Geary, Roman booty was not the focus of Alaric's sack of Rome; he came for needed food supplies.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Certainly the Roman world was shaken by the fall of the Eternal City to barbarian invaders, but as Guy Halsall emphasizes, "Rome's fall had less striking political effects.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Still, the importance of Alaric cannot be "overestimated" according to Halsall, since he had desired and obtained a Roman command even though he was a barbarian; his real misfortune was being caught between the rivalry of the Eastern and Western empires and their court intrigue.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Whether Alaric's forces wrought the level of destruction described by Procopius or not cannot be known, but evidence speaks to a significant population decrease, as the number of people on the food dole dropped from 800,000 in 408 to 500,000 by 419.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Rome's fall to the barbarians was as much a psychological blow to the empire as anything else, since some Romans citizens saw the collapse as resulting from the conversion to Christianity, while Christian theologians like St.Augustine (writing *City of God*) responded in turn.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Not only had Rome's sack been a significant blow to the Roman people's morale, they had also endured two years' worth of trauma brought about by fear, hunger (due to blockades), and illness.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] However, the Goths were not long in the city of Rome, as only three days after the sack, Alaric marched his men south to Campania, from where he intended to sail to Sicily—probably to obtain grain and other supplies—when a storm destroyed his fleet.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] During the early months of 411, while on his northward return journey through Italy, Alaric took ill and died at Consentia in Bruttium.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] His cause of death was likely fever, and his body was, according to legend, buried under the riverbed of the Busento in accordance with the pagan practices of the Visigothic people.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] The stream was temporarily turned aside from its course while the grave was dug, wherein the Gothic chief and some of his most precious spoils were interred.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] When the work was finished, the river was turned back into its usual channel and the captives by whose hands the labour had been accomplished were put to death that none might learn their secret.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric was succeeded in the command of the Gothic army by his brother-in-law, Ataulf, who married Honorius's sister Galla Placidia three years later.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Following in the wake of Alaric's leadership, which Kulikowski claims, had given his people "a sense of community that survived his own death ...
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Alaric's Goths remained together inside the empire, going on to settle in Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] There, in the province of Aquitaine, they put down roots and created the first autonomous barbarian kingdom inside the frontiers of the Roman empire." The Goths were able to settle in Aquitaine only after Honorius granted the once Roman province to them, sometime in 418 or 419.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] Not long after Alaric's exploits in Rome and Athaulf's settlement in Aquitaine, there is a "rapid emergence of Germanic barbarian groups in the West" who begin controlling many western provinces.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alaric-i] These barbarian peoples included: Vandals in Spain and Africa, Visigoths in Spain and Aquitaine, Burgundians along the upper Rhine and southern Gaul, and Franks on the lower Rhine and in northern and central Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The **Alemanni** or **Alamanni** were a confederation of Germanic tribes on the Upper Rhine River during the 1st millennium.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In 496 AD, the Alemanni were conquered by the Frankish leader Clovis and incorporated into his dominions.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Mentioned as still pagan allies of the Christian Franks, the Alemanni were gradually Christianized during the 7th century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The *Lex Alamannorum* is a record of their customary law during this period.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Until the 8th century, Frankish suzerainty over Alemannia was mostly nominal.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] However, after an uprising by Theudebald, the Duke of Alamannia, Carloman executed the Alamannic nobility and installed Frankish dukes.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] As the Carolingian Empire weakened in later years, the Alemannic counts became almost independent, and a struggle for supremacy took place between them and the Bishopric of Constance.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The chief family in Alamannia was that of the counts of *Raetia Curiensis*, who were sometimes called margraves, and one of whom, Burchard II, established the Duchy of Swabia, which was recognized by Henry the Fowler in 919 AD and became a stem duchy of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The area settled by the Alemanni corresponds roughly to the area where Alemannic German dialects remain spoken, including German Swabia and Baden, French Alsace, German-speaking Switzerland, Liechtenstein and Austrian Vorarlberg.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The French-language name of Germany, *Allemagne*, is derived from their name, from Old French *aleman(t)*, and from French was loaned into a number of other languages, including Middle English, which commonly used the term *Almains* for Germans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Likewise, the Arabic name for Germany is ألمانيا (*Almanya*), the Turkish is *Almanya*, the Catalan is *Alemanya*, the Spanish is *Alemania*, the Portuguese is *Alemanha*, the Welsh is *Yr Almaen* and the Persian is آلمان (*Alman*).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] According to Gaius Asinius Quadratus (quoted in the mid-sixth century by Byzantine historian Agathias), the name *Alamanni* (Ἀλαμανοι) means "all men".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] It indicates that they were a conglomeration drawn from various Germanic tribes.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Romans and the Greeks called them as such (Alamanni, all men, in the sense of a group composed of men of all groups in the region).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] This derivation was accepted by Edward Gibbon, in his *Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire* and by the anonymous contributor of notes assembled from the papers of Nicolas Fréret, published in 1753.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] This etymology has remained the standard derivation of the name.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] An alternative suggestion proposes derivation from **alah* "sanctuary".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Walafrid Strabo in the ninth century remarked, in discussing the people of Switzerland and the surrounding regions, that only foreigners called them the Alemanni, but that they gave themselves the name of *Suebi*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Suebi are given the alternative name of *Ziuwari* (as *Cyuuari*) in an Old High German gloss, interpreted by Jacob Grimm as *Martem colentes* ("worshippers of Mars").
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Annio da Viterbo a scholar and historian of the 15th century claimed the Alemanni had their name from the Hebrew language, as in Hebrew the river Rhine was translated into *Mannum* and the people who live at its shores were called *Alemannus*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] This was refuted by Beatus Rhenanus, a humanist of the 16th century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Rhenanus argued the term Alemanni was meant for the whole Germanic people only in late antiquity and before it was only meant to designate the population of an island in the North Sea.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Early Roman writers did not mention the Alemanni, and it is likely that they had not yet come to exist.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In his *Germania* Tacitus (AD 90) does not mention the Alemanni.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] He uses the term Agri Decumates to describe the region between the Rhine, Main and Danube rivers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] He says that it had once been the home of the Helvetians, who had moved westwards into Gaul in the time of Julius Caesar.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The people living there in Caesar's time are not Germanic.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Instead, "Reckless adventurers from Gaul, emboldened by want, occupied this land of questionable ownership.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Alemanni were first mentioned by Cassius Dio describing the campaign of Caracalla in 213.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] At that time, they apparently dwelt in the basin of the Main, to the south of the Chatti.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Cassius Dio portrays the Alemanni as victims of this treacherous emperor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] They had asked for his help, according to Dio, but instead he colonized their country, changed their place names, and executed their warriors under a pretext of coming to their aid.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] When he became ill, the Alemanni claimed to have put a hex on him.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Caracalla, it was claimed, tried to counter this influence by invoking his ancestral spirits.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In retribution, Caracalla then led the Legio II *Traiana Fortis* against the Alemanni, who lost and were pacified for a time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Through much of his short reign, Caracalla was known for unpredictable and arbitrary operations launched by surprise after a pretext of peace negotiations.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] If he had any reasons of state for such actions, they remained unknown to his contemporaries.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Whether or not the Alemanni had been previously neutral, they were certainly further influenced by Caracalla to become thereafter notoriously implacable enemies of Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Most of the Alemanni were probably at the time, in fact, resident in or close to the borders of Germania Superior.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Although Dio is the earliest writer to mention them, Ammianus Marcellinus used the name to refer to Germans on the Limes Germanicus in the time of Trajan's governorship of the province shortly after it was formed, around 98–99 AD.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] At that time, the entire frontier was being fortified for the first time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Trees from the earliest fortifications found in Germania Inferior are dated by dendrochronology to 99–100 AD.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Ammianus relates (xvii.1.11) that much later the Emperor Julian undertook a punitive expedition against the Alemanni, who by then were in Alsace, and crossed the Main (Latin *Menus*), entering the forest, where the trails were blocked by felled trees.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] As winter was upon them, they reoccupied a "fortification which was founded on the soil of the Alemanni that Trajan wished to be called with his own name".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In this context, the use of Alemanni is possibly an anachronism, but it reveals that Ammianus believed they were the same people, which is consistent with the location of the Alemanni of Caracalla's campaigns.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Alemanni were continually engaged in conflicts with the Roman Empire in the third and fourth centuries.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] They launched a major invasion of Gaul and northern Italy in 268 when the Romans were forced to denude much of their German frontier of troops in response to a massive invasion of the Goths from the east.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] And coming to Clermont he set on fire, overthrew and destroyed that shrine which they call *Vasso Galatae* in the Gallic tongue," martyring many Christians (*Historia Francorum* Book I.32–34).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Thus sixth-century Gallo-Romans of Gregory's class, surrounded by the ruins of Roman temples and public buildings, attributed the destruction they saw to the plundering raids of the Alemanni.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In the early summer of 268, the Emperor Gallienus halted their advance into Italy but then had to deal with the Goths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] When the Gothic campaign ended in Roman victory at the Battle of Naissus in September, Gallienus's successor Claudius Gothicus turned north to deal with the Alemanni, who were swarming over all Italy north of the Po River.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] After efforts to secure a peaceful withdrawal failed, Claudius forced the Alemanni to battle at the Battle of Lake Benacus in November.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Alemanni were routed, forced back into Germany, and did not threaten Roman territory for many years afterwards.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Their most famous battle against Rome took place in Argentoratum (Strasbourg), in 357, where they were defeated by Julian, later Emperor of Rome, and their king Chnodomarius was taken prisoner to Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] On January 2, 366, the Alemanni yet again crossed the frozen Rhine in large numbers, to invade the Gallic provinces, this time being defeated by Valentinian (see Battle of Solicinium).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In the great mixed invasion of 406, the Alemanni appear to have crossed the Rhine river a final time, conquering and then settling what is today Alsace and a large part of the Swiss Plateau.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The crossing is described in Wallace Breem's historical novel *Eagle in the Snow*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Chronicle of Fredegar gives the account.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] At *Alba Augusta* (Alba-la-Romaine) the devastation was so complete, that the Christian bishop retired to Viviers, but in Gregory's account at Mende in Lozère, also deep in the heart of Gaul, bishop Privatus was forced to sacrifice to idols in the very cave where he was later venerated.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] It is thought this detail may be a generic literary ploy to epitomize the horrors of barbarian violence.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The kingdom of Alamannia between Strasbourg and Augsburg lasted until 496, when the Alemanni were conquered by Clovis I at the Battle of Tolbiac.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The war of Clovis with the Alemanni forms the setting for the conversion of Clovis, briefly treated by Gregory of Tours.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] (Book II.31) After their defeat in 496, the Alemanni bucked the Frankish yoke and put themselves under the protection of Theodoric the Great of the Ostrogoths but after his death they were again subjugated by the Franks under Theudebert I in 536.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Subsequently, the Alemanni formed part of the Frankish dominions and were governed by a Frankish duke.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In 746, Carloman ended an uprising by summarily executing all Alemannic nobility at the blood court at Cannstatt, and for the following century, Alemannia was ruled by Frankish dukes.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Following the treaty of Verdun of 843, Alemannia became a province of the eastern kingdom of Louis the German, the precursor of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The German spoken today over the range of the former Alemanni is termed Alemannic German, and is recognised among the subgroups of the High German languages.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Alemannic runic inscriptions such as those on the Pforzen buckle are among the earliest testimonies of Old High German.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The High German consonant shift is thought to have originated around the fifth century either in Alemannia or among the Lombards; before that, the dialect spoken by Alemannic tribes was little different from that of other West Germanic peoples.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Alemanni established a series of territorially defined *pagi* (cantons) on the east bank of the Rhine.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The exact number and extent of these *pagi* is unclear and probably changed over time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Christianization of the Alemanni took place during Merovingian times (sixth to eighth centuries).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] We know that in the sixth century, the Alemanni were predominantly pagan, and in the eighth century, they were predominantly Christian.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The intervening seventh century was a period of genuine syncretism during which Christian symbolism and doctrine gradually grew in influence.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Some scholars have speculated that members of the Alemannic elite such as king Gibuld due to Visigothic influence may have been converted to Arianism even in the later fifth century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] He also spoke of the particular ruthlessness of the Alemanni in destroying Christian sanctuaries and plundering churches while the genuine Franks were respectful towards those sanctuaries.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Agathias expresses his hope that the Alemanni would assume better manners through prolonged contact with the Franks, which is by all appearances, in a manner of speaking, what eventually happened.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Apostles of the Alemanni were Columbanus and his disciple Saint Gall.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Jonas of Bobbio records that Columbanus was active in Bregenz, where he disrupted a beer sacrifice to Wodan.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Despite these activities, for some time, the Alemanni seem to have continued their pagan cult activities, with only superficial or syncretistic Christian elements.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In particular, there was no change in burial practice, and tumulus warrior graves continued to be erected throughout Merovingian times.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Syncretism of traditional Germanic animal style with Christian symbolism is also present in artwork, but Christian symbolism became more and more prevalent during the seventh century.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Unlike the later Christianization of the Saxons and of the Slavs, the Alemanni seem to have adopted Christianity gradually, and voluntarily, spread in emulation of the Merovingian elite.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] From c. the 520s to the 620s, there was a surge of Alemannic Elder Futhark inscriptions.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] About 70 specimens have survived, roughly half of them on fibulae, others on belt buckles (see Pforzen buckle, Bülach fibula) and other jewellery and weapon parts.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The use of runes subsides with the advance of Christianity.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The Nordendorf fibula (early seventh century) clearly records pagan theonyms, *logaþorewodanwigiþonar* read as "Wodan and Donar are magicians/sorcerers", but this may be interpreted as either a pagan invocation of the powers of these deities, or a Christian protective charm against them.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] A runic inscription on a fibula found at Bad Ems reflects Christian pious sentiment (and is also explicitly marked with a Christian cross), reading *god fura dih deofile ᛭* ("God for/before you, Theophilus!", or alternatively "God before you, Devil!").
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Dated to between AD 660 and 690, it marks the end of the native Alemannic tradition of runic literacy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Bad Ems is in Rhineland-Palatinate, on the northwestern boundary of Alemannic settlement, where Frankish influence would have been strongest.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The establishment of the bishopric of Konstanz cannot be dated exactly and was possibly undertaken by Columbanus himself (before 612).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In any case, it existed by 635, when Gunzo appointed John of Grab bishop.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Constance was a missionary bishopric in newly converted lands, and did not look back on late Roman church history unlike the Raetian bishopric of Chur (established 451) and Basel (an episcopal seat from 740, and which continued the line of Bishops of Augusta Raurica, see Bishop of Basel).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The establishment of the church as an institution recognized by worldly rulers is also visible in legal history.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] In the early seventh century *Pactus Alamannorum* hardly ever mentions the special privileges of the church, while Lantfrid's *Lex Alamannorum* of 720 has an entire chapter reserved for ecclesial matters alone.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] A genetic study published in *Science Advances* in September 2018 examined the remains of eight individuals buried at a seventh-century Alemannic graveyard in Niederstotzingen, Germany.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] This is the richest and most complete Alemannic graveyard ever found.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The highest-ranking individual at the graveyard was a male with Frankish grave goods.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Four males were found to be closely related to him.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] They were all carriers of types of the paternal haplogroup R1b1a2a1a1c2b2b.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] A sixth male was a carrier of the paternal haplogroup R1b1a2a1a1c2b2b1a1 and the maternal haplogroup U5a1a1.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Along with the five closely related individuals, he displayed close genetic links to northern and eastern Europe, particularly Lithuania and Iceland.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Two individuals buried at the cemetery were found to be genetically different from both the others and each other, displaying genetic links to Southern Europe, particularly northern Italy and Spain.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] Along with the sixth male, they might have been adoptees or slaves.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] The data indicate a significant increase in Scandinavian-related ancestry—a proxy for Germanic-speaking groups—in the first half of the first millennium AD, with "median northern European ancestry" rising significantly, reaching high levels in the early medieval period.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/alemanni] This population turnover was associated with the introduction of new paternal haplogroups, such as I1-M253, which is commonly found in "Continental North European-like ancestry".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The **sack of Rome** on 24 August 410 AD was undertaken by the Visigoths led by their king, Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] At that time, Rome was no longer the administrative capital of the Western Roman Empire, having been replaced first by Mediolanum (now Milan) in 286 and then by Ravenna in 402.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Nevertheless, the city of Rome retained a paramount position as "the eternal city" and a spiritual center of the Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] This was the first time in almost 800 years that Rome had fallen to a foreign enemy, and the sack was a major shock to contemporaries, friends and foes of the Empire alike.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The sacking of 410 is seen as a major landmark in the fall of the Western Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jerome, living in Bethlehem, wrote: "the city which had taken the whole world was itself taken".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Germanic tribes had undergone massive technological, social, and economic changes after four centuries of contact with the Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] From the first to fourth centuries, their populations, economic production, and tribal confederations grew, and their ability to conduct warfare increased to the point of challenging Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Goths, one of the Germanic tribes, had invaded the Roman Empire on and off since 238.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] But in the late 4th century, the Huns began to invade the lands of the Germanic tribes, and pushed many of them into the Roman Empire with greater fervor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] In 376, the Huns forced many Therving Goths led by Fritigern and Alavivus to seek refuge in the Eastern Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Soon after, starvation, high taxes, hatred from the Roman population, and governmental corruption turned the Goths against the empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Goths rebelled and began looting and pillaging throughout the eastern Balkans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] A Roman army, led by the Eastern Roman emperor Valens, marched to put them down.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] At the Battle of Adrianople in 378, Fritigern decisively defeated emperor Valens, who was killed in battle.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Peace was eventually established in 382 when the new Eastern emperor, Theodosius I, signed a treaty with the Thervings, who would become known as the Visigoths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The treaty made the Visigoths subjects of the empire as foederati.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] They were allotted the northern part of the dioceses of Dacia and Thrace, and while the land remained under Roman sovereignty and the Visigoths were expected to provide military service, they were considered autonomous.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Possibly in 391, a Gothic chieftain named Alaric was declared king by a group of Visigoths, though there is debate over the nature of his position and the year of his ascension (Jordanes says 400, Peter Heather says 395).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He then led an invasion into Eastern Roman territory outside of the Goths' designated lands.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric was defeated by Theodosius and his general Flavius Stilicho in 392, who forced Alaric back into Roman vassalage.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] In 394, Alaric led a force of Visigoths as part of Theodosius's Eastern Roman army to invade the Western Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] At the Battle of the Frigidus, around half the Visigoths present died fighting the Western Roman army led by the usurper Eugenius and his general Arbogast.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Theodosius won the battle, and although Alaric was given the title *comes* for his bravery, tensions between the Goths and Romans grew as it seemed the Roman generals had sought to weaken the Goths by making them bear the brunt of the fighting.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric was also enraged he had not been granted a higher office in the imperial administration.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] When Theodosius died on 10 January 395, the Visigoths considered their 382 treaty with Rome to have ended.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric quickly led his warriors back to their lands in Moesia, gathered most of the federated Goths in the Danubian provinces under his leadership, and rose in rebellion, invading Thrace and approaching the Eastern Roman capital of Constantinople.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Huns, at the same moment, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The death of Theodosius had also wracked the political structure of the empire: Theodosius's sons, Honorius and Arcadius, were given the Western and Eastern empires, respectively, but they were young and needed guidance.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] A power struggle emerged between Stilicho, who claimed guardianship over both emperors but was still in the West with the army that had defeated Eugenius, and Rufinus, the praetorian prefect of the East, who took the guardianship of Arcadius in the Eastern capital of Constantinople.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho claimed that Theodosius had awarded him with sole guardianship on the emperor's deathbed and claimed authority over the Eastern Empire as well as the West.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Rufinus negotiated with Alaric to get him to withdraw from Constantinople (perhaps by promising him lands in Thessaly).
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Whatever the case, Alaric marched away from Constantinople to Greece, looting the diocese of Macedonia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho obeyed the orders of his emperor by sending his Eastern troops to Constantinople and leading his Western ones back to Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Eastern troops Stilicho had sent to Constantinople were led by a Goth named Gainas.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] When Rufinus met the soldiers, he was hacked to death in November 395.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Whether that was done on the orders of Stilicho, or perhaps on those of Rufinus's replacement Eutropius, is unknown.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The withdrawal of Stilicho freed Alaric to pillage much of Greece, including Piraeus, Corinth, Argos, and Sparta.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Athens was able to pay a ransom to avoid being sacked.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] It was only in 397 that Stilicho returned to Greece, having rebuilt his army with mainly barbarian allies and believing the eastern Roman government would now welcome his arrival.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] After some fighting, Stilicho trapped and besieged Alaric at Pholoe.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Then, once again, Stilicho retreated to Italy, and Alaric marched into Epirus.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Why Stilicho once again failed to dispatch Alaric is a matter of contention.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] It has been suggested that Stilicho's mostly-barbarian army had been unreliable or that another order from Arcadius and the Eastern government forced his withdrawal.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Others suggest that Stilicho made an agreement with Alaric and betrayed the East.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Whatever the case, Stilicho was declared a public enemy in the Eastern Empire the same year.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric's rampage in Epirus was enough to make the eastern Roman government offer him terms in 398.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] They made Alaric *magister militum per Illyricum*, giving him the Roman command he wanted and giving him free rein to take what resources he needed, including armaments, in his assigned province.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho, in the meantime, put down a rebellion in Africa in 399, which had been instigated by the eastern Roman empire, and married his daughter Maria to the 11-year-old Western emperor, Honorius, strengthening his grip on power in the West.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Aurelianus, the new praetorian prefect of the east after Eutropius's execution, stripped Alaric of his title to Illyricum in 400.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Between 700 and 7,000 Gothic soldiers and their families were slaughtered in a riot at Constantinople on 12 July 400.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Gainas, who at one point had been made *magister militum*, rebelled, but he was killed by the Huns under Uldin, who sent his head back to Constantinople as a gift.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] With these events, particularly Rome's use of the feared Huns, and cut off from Roman officialdom, Alaric felt his position in the East was precarious.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] So, while Stilicho was busy fighting an invasion of Vandals and Alans in Rhaetia and Noricum, Alaric led his people into an invasion of Italy in 401, reaching it in November without encountering much resistance.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Goths captured a few unnamed cities and besieged the Western Roman capital Mediolanum.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho, now with Alan and Vandal federates in his army, relieved the siege, forcing a crossing at the Adda river.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] On Easter Sunday, 6 April 402, Stilicho launched a surprise attack which became the Battle of Pollentia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The battle ended in a draw, and Alaric fell back.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] After brief negotiations and maneuvers, the two forces clashed again at the Battle of Verona, where Alaric was defeated and besieged in a mountain fortress, taking heavy casualties.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] At this point, a number of Goths in Alaric's army started deserting him, including Sarus, who went over to the Romans.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric and his army then withdrew to the borderlands next to Dalmatia and Pannonia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius, fearful after the near capture of Mediolanum, moved the Western Roman capital to Ravenna, which was more defensible with its natural swamps and more escapable with its access to the sea.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Moving the capital to Ravenna may have disconnected the Western court from events beyond the Alps towards a preoccupation with the defense of Italy, weakening the Western Empire as a whole.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] In time, Alaric became an ally of Stilicho, agreeing to help claim the praetorian prefecture of Illyricum for the Western Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] To that end, Stilicho named Alaric *magister militum* of Illyricum in 405.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] However, the Goth Radagaisus invaded Italy that same year, putting any such plans on hold.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho and the Romans, reinforced by Alans, Goths under Sarus, and Huns under Uldin, managed to defeat Radagaisus in August 406, but only after the devastation of northern Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] 12,000 of Radagaisus's Goths were pressed into Roman military service, and others were enslaved.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] So many were sold into slavery by the victorious Roman forces that slave prices temporarily collapsed.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Only in 407 did Stilicho turn his attention back to Illyricum, gathering a fleet to support Alaric's proposed invasion.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] But then the Rhine *limes* collapsed under the weight of hordes of Vandals, Suebi, and Alans who flooded into Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Roman population attacked there thus rose in rebellion under the usurper Constantine III.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho reconciled with the Eastern Roman Empire in 408, and the Visigoths under Alaric had lost their value to Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric then invaded and took control of parts of Noricum and upper Pannonia in the spring of 408.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He demanded 288,000 solidi (four thousand pounds of gold), and threatened to invade Italy if he did not get it.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] This was equivalent to the amount of money earned in property revenue by a single senatorial family in one year.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Only with the greatest difficulty was Stilicho able to get the Roman Senate to agree to pay the ransom, which was to buy the Romans a new alliance with Alaric who was to go to Gaul and fight the usurper Constantine III.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The debate on whether to pay Alaric weakened Stilicho's relationship with Honorius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Before payment could be received, however, the Eastern Roman Emperor Arcadius died of illness on 1 May 408.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He was succeeded by his young son, Theodosius II.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius wanted to go East to secure his nephew's succession, but Stilicho convinced him to stay and allow Stilicho himself to go instead.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Olympius, a palatine official and an enemy of Stilicho's, spread false rumors that Stilicho planned to place his own son Eucherius on the throne of the East, and many came to believe them.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Roman soldiers mutinied and began killing officials who were known supporters of Stilicho.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho's barbarian troops offered to attack the mutineers, but Stilicho forbade it.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho instead went to Ravenna to meet with the Emperor to resolve the crisis.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius, now believing the rumors of Stilicho's treason, ordered his arrest.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho sought sanctuary in a church in Ravenna, but he was lured out with promises of safety.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stepping outside, he was arrested and told he was to be immediately executed on Honorius's orders.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho refused to allow his followers to resist, and he was executed on 22 August 408.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Stilicho's execution stopped the payment to Alaric and his Visigoths, who had received none of it.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The half-Vandal, half-Roman general is credited with keeping the Western Roman Empire from crumbling during his 13 years of rule, and his death would have profound repercussions for the West.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] His son Eucherius was executed shortly after in Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Olympius was appointed *magister officiorum* and replaced Stilicho as the power behind the throne.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] His new government was strongly anti-Germanic and obsessed with purging any and all of Stilicho's former supporters.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Roman soldiers began to indiscriminately slaughter allied barbarian foederati soldiers and their families in Roman cities.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Thousands of them fled Italy and sought refuge with Alaric in Noricum.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Zosimus reports the number of refugees as 30,000, but Peter Heather and Thomas Burns believe that number is impossibly high.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Heather argues that Zosimus had misread his source and that 30,000 is the total number of fighting-men under Alaric's command after the refugees joined Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Attempting to come to an agreement with Honorius, Alaric asked for hostages, gold, and permission to move to Pannonia, but Honorius refused.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric, aware of the weakened state of defenses in Italy, invaded in early October, six weeks after Stilicho's death.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He also sent word of this news to his brother-in-law Ataulf asking him to join the invasion as soon as he was able with reinforcements.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric and his Visigoths sacked Ariminum and other cities as they moved south.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric's march was unopposed and leisurely, as if they were going to a festival, according to Zosimus.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Sarus and his band of Goths, still in Italy, remained neutral and aloof.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The city of Rome may have held as many as 800,000 people, making it the largest in the world at the time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Goths under Alaric laid siege to the city in late 408.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Panic swept through its streets, and there was an attempt to reinstate pagan rituals in the still religiously mixed city to ward off the Visigoths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Pope Innocent I even agreed to it, provided it be done in private.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The pagan priests, however, said the sacrifices could only be done publicly in the Roman Forum, and the idea was abandoned.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Serena, the wife of the proscribed Stilicho and a cousin of emperor Honorius, was in the city and believed by the Roman populace, with little evidence, to be encouraging Alaric's invasion.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Galla Placidia, the sister of the emperor Honorius, was also trapped in the city and gave her consent to the Roman Senate to execute Serena, who was then strangled to death.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Hopes of help from the Imperial government faded as the siege continued and Alaric took control of the Tiber River, which cut the supplies going into Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Grain was rationed to one-half and then one-third of its previous amount.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Starvation and disease rapidly spread throughout the city, and rotting bodies were left unburied in the streets.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Roman Senate then decided to send two envoys to Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] One envoy asked what would be left to the citizens of Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Ultimately, the city was forced to give the Goths 5,000 pounds of gold, 30,000 pounds of silver, 4,000 silken tunics, 3,000 hides dyed scarlet, and 3,000 pounds of pepper in exchange for lifting the siege.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The barbarian slaves fled to Alaric as well, swelling his ranks to about 40,000.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Many of the barbarian slaves were probably Radagaisus's former followers.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] To raise the needed money, Roman senators were to contribute according to their means.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] This led to corruption and abuse, and the sum came up short.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Romans then stripped down and melted pagan statues and shrines to make up the difference.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Zosimus reports one such statue was of Virtus, and that when it was melted down to pay off barbarians it seemed "all that remained of the Roman valor and intrepidity was totally extinguished".
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius consented to the payment of the ransom, and with it the Visigoths lifted the siege and withdrew to Etruria in December 408.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] In January 409, the Senate sent an embassy to the imperial court at Ravenna to encourage the Emperor to come to terms with the Goths, and to give Roman aristocratic children as hostages to the Goths as insurance.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric would then resume his alliance with the Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius, under the influence of Olympius, refused and called in five legions from Dalmatia, totaling six thousand men.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] They were to go to Rome and garrison the city, but their commander, a man named Valens, marched his men into Etruria, believing it cowardly to go around the Goths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He and his men were intercepted and attacked by Alaric's full force, and almost all were killed or captured.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Only 100 managed to escape and reach Rome.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] A second Senatorial embassy, this time including Pope Innocent I, was sent with Gothic guards to Honorius to plead with him to accept the Visigoths' demands.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The imperial government also received word that Ataulf, Alaric's brother-in-law, had crossed the Julian Alps with his Goths into Italy with the intent of joining Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius summoned together all available Roman forces in northern Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He placed 300 Huns of the imperial guard under the command of Olympius, and possibly the other forces as well, and ordered him to intercept Ataulf.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] They clashed near Pisa, and despite his force supposedly killing 1,100 Goths and losing only 17 of his own men, Olympius was forced to retreat back to Ravenna.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Zosimus seems to imply that only the Huns under Olympius took part in this fight.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] This failure caused Olympius to fall from power and to flee for his life to Dalmatia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jovius, the praetorian prefect of Italy, replaced Olympius as the power behind the throne and received the title of *patrician*.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jovius engineered a mutiny of soldiers in Ravenna who demanded the killing of *magister utriusque militiae* Turpilio and *magister equitum* Vigilantius; he had both men killed.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jovius was a friend of Alaric's and had been a supporter of Stilicho, and thus the new government was open to negotiations.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric went to Ariminum to meet Jovius and present his demands.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric wanted yearly tribute in gold and grain, and lands in the provinces of Dalmatia, Noricum, and Venetia for his people.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jovius also wrote privately to Honorius, suggesting that if Alaric was offered the position of *magister utriusque militiae*, they could lessen Alaric's other demands.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius rejected the demand for a Roman office, and he sent an insulting letter to Alaric, which was read out in the negotiations.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Infuriated, Alaric broke off negotiations, and Jovius returned to Ravenna to strengthen his relationship with the Emperor.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius was now firmly committed to war, and Jovius swore on the Emperor's head never to make peace with Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric himself soon changed his mind when he heard Honorius was attempting to recruit 10,000 Huns to fight the Goths.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He gathered a group of Roman bishops and sent them to Honorius with his new terms.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He no longer sought Roman office or tribute in gold.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He now only requested lands in Noricum and as much grain as the Emperor found necessary.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Historian Olympiodorus the Younger, writing many years later, considered these terms extremely moderate and reasonable.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] But it was too late: Honorius's government, bound by oath and intent on war, rejected the offer.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric took Portus and renewed the siege of Rome in late 409.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Faced with the return of starvation and disease, the Senate met with Alaric.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He demanded that they appoint one of their own as Emperor to rival Honorius, and he instigated the election of the elderly Priscus Attalus to that end, a pagan who permitted himself to be baptized.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric was then made *magister utriusque militiae* and his brother-in-law Ataulf was given the position *comes domesticorum equitum* in the new, rival government, and the siege was lifted.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Heraclian, governor of the food-rich province of Africa, remained loyal to Honorius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Attalus sent a Roman force to subdue him, refusing to send Gothic soldiers there as he was distrustful of their intentions.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Attalus and Alaric then marched to Ravenna, forcing some cities in northern Italy to submit to Attalus.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius, extremely fearful at this turn of events, sent Jovius and others to Attalus, pleading that they share the Western Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Attalus said he would only negotiate on Honorius's place of exile.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jovius, for his part, switched sides to Attalus and was named patrician by his new master.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jovius wanted to have Honorius mutilated as well (something that was to become common in the Eastern Empire), but Attalus rejected it.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Increasingly isolated and now in pure panic, Honorius was preparing to flee to Constantinople when 4,000 Eastern Roman soldiers appeared at Ravenna's docks to defend the city.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Their arrival strengthened Honorius's resolve to await news of what had happened in Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Heraclian had defeated Attalus's force and cut supplies to Rome, threatening another famine in the city.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric wanted to send Gothic soldiers to invade Africa and secure the province, but Attalus again refused, distrustful of the Visigoths' intentions for the province.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Counseled by Jovius to do away with his puppet emperor, Alaric summoned Attalus to Ariminum and ceremonially stripped him of his imperial regalia and title in the summer of 410.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric then reopened negotiations with Honorius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Honorius arranged for a meeting with Alaric about 12 kilometres outside of Ravenna.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] As Alaric waited at the meeting place, Sarus, who was a sworn enemy of Ataulf and now allied to Honorius, attacked Alaric and his men with a small Roman force.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Peter Heather speculates Sarus had also lost the election for the kingship of the Goths to Alaric in the 390s.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric survived the attack and, outraged at this treachery and frustrated by all the past failures at accommodation, gave up on negotiating with Honorius and headed back to Rome, which he besieged for the third and final time.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] On 24 August 410 the Visigoths entered Rome through its Salarian Gate, according to some opened by treachery, according to others by want of food, and pillaged the city for three days.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Many of the city's great buildings were ransacked, including the mausoleums of Augustus and Hadrian, in which many emperors of the past were buried; the ashes of the urns in both tombs were scattered.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Any and all moveable goods were stolen all over the city.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Some of the few places the Goths spared were the two major basilicas connected to Peter and Paul, though from the Lateran Palace they stole a massive, 2,025-pound silver ciborium that had been a gift from Constantine.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Structural damage to buildings was largely limited to the areas near the old Senate house and the Salarian Gate, where the Gardens of Sallust were burned and never rebuilt.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Basilica Aemilia and the Basilica Julia were also burned.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Many Romans were taken captive, including the Emperor's sister, Galla Placidia.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Some citizens would be ransomed, others would be sold into slavery, and still others would be raped and killed.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Pelagius, a Roman monk from Britain, survived the siege and wrote an account of the experience in a letter to a young woman named Demetrias.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Many Romans were tortured into revealing the locations of their valuables.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] One was the 85-year-old Saint Marcella, who had no hidden gold as she lived in pious poverty.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jerome, and he detailed the incident in a letter to a woman named Principia who had been with Marcella during the sack.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Marcella died of her injuries a few days later.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The sack was nonetheless, by the standards of the age, restrained.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] There was no general slaughter or wholesale enslavement of the city's inhabitants and the two main basilicas of Peter and Paul were nominated places of sanctuary.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Most of the buildings and monuments in the city survived intact, though stripped of their valuables.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Refugees from Rome flooded the province of Africa, as well as Egypt and the East.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Some refugees were robbed as they sought asylum, and St.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jerome wrote that Heraclian, the Count of Africa, sold some of the young refugees into Eastern brothels.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] After three days of looting and pillage, Alaric quickly left Rome and headed for southern Italy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] He took with him the wealth of the city and a valuable hostage, Galla Placidia, the sister of emperor Honorius.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Visigoths ravaged Campania, Lucania, and Calabria.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Nola and perhaps Capua were sacked, and the Visigoths threatened to invade Sicily and Africa.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] However, they were unable to cross the Strait of Messina as the ships they had gathered were wrecked by a storm.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Alaric died of illness at Consentia in late 410, mere months after the sack.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] According to legend, he was buried with his treasure by slaves in the bed of the Busento river.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The slaves were then killed to hide its location.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Visigoths elected Ataulf, Alaric's brother-in-law, as their new king.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Visigoths then moved north, heading for Gaul.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Ataulf married Galla Placidia in 414, but he died one year later.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Visigoths established the Visigothic Kingdom in southwestern Gaul in 418, and they would go on to help the Western Roman Empire fight Attila the Hun at the Battle of the Catalaunian Fields in 451.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Visigothic invasion of Italy caused land taxes to drop anywhere from one-fifth to one-ninth of their pre-invasion value in the affected provinces.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Aristocratic munificence, the local support of public buildings and monuments by the upper classes, ended in south-central Italy after the sack and pillaging of those regions.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Using the number of people on the food dole as a guide, Bertrand Lançon estimates the city of Rome's total population fell from 800,000 in 408 to 500,000 by 419.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] This was the first time the city of Rome had been sacked in almost 800 years, and it had revealed the Western Roman Empire's increasing vulnerability and military weakness.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] It was shocking to people across both halves of the Empire who viewed Rome as the eternal city and the symbolic heart of their empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Eastern Roman Emperor Theodosius II declared three days of mourning in Constantinople.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Jerome wrote in grief, "If Rome can perish, what can be safe?" In Bethlehem, he detailed his shock in the preface to his commentary on Ezekiel.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Roman Empire at this time was still in the midst of religious conflict between pagans and Christians.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The sack was used by both sides to bolster their competing claims of divine legitimacy.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Paulus Orosius, a Christian priest and theologian, believed the sack was God's wrath against a proud and blasphemous city, and that it was only through God's benevolence that the sack had not been too severe.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Rome had lost its wealth, but Roman sovereignty endured, and that to talk to the survivors in Rome one would think "nothing had happened." Other Romans felt the sack was divine punishment for turning away from the traditional pagan gods to Christ.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Zosimus, a Roman pagan historian, believed that Christianity, through its abandonment of the ancient traditional rites, had weakened the Empire's political virtues, and that the poor decisions of the Imperial government that led to the sack were due to the lack of the gods' care.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The religious and political attacks on Christianity spurred Saint Augustine to write a defense, *The City of God*, which went on to become foundational to Christian thought.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The sack was a culmination of many terminal problems facing the Western Roman Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] Domestic rebellions and usurpations weakened the Empire in the face of external invasions.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] These factors would permanently harm the stability of the Roman Empire in the west.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] The Roman army meanwhile became increasingly barbarian and disloyal to the Empire.
[src:sack-of-rome-410/sack-of-rome-410] A more severe sack of Rome by the Vandals followed in 455, and the Western Roman Empire finally collapsed in 476 when the Germanic Odovacer removed the last Western Roman Emperor, Romulus Augustulus, and declared himself King of Italy.
